<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-159-464 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 711 077</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  May 6 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Australia: Telecom to apply price cap on its suppliers.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>McNamara, Sean.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Telecom Australia (Prices and rates).andO;Topic:     Pricing PolicyContractsAustraliaSupplies.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>AUSTRALIA: TELECOM TO APPLY PRICE CAP ON ITS SUPPLIERS 05/06/91 SYDNEY,AUSTRALIA, 1991 MAY 6 (NB) -- Slugged with a price cap for the services itprovides, Telecom has announced it will impose a price cap on its suppliers.andO;Telecom is Australia's national carrier, and it carries enough muscle in theAustralian electronics industry for such an audacious move.andM;Telecom is about to have a price cap applied to telephone call charges, andthe cap will mean that call charges will fall by at least 5.5 percent a yearin real terms.andP;  The move will involve regular electronics suppliers toTelecom increasing prices for their goods according to the equation CPI-2.andO;This means suppliers will have to limit increases to 2 percent below the CPI.andO;The CPI is the Consumer Price Index, the official Australian inflation rateas a percentage.andP;  Telecom is currently formulating the official price cappolicy to be distributed to suppliers, and this may include the software andtelecommunications products sectors as Telecom invests more heavily in thoseareas.andM;Telecom currently accounts for around 85 percent of revenue for the localelectronics industry, and it is because of this dominant purchasing positionthat Telecom feels it can make a move which it describes as &quot;provocative.&quot;andO;This position is not likely to change in the near future, with the AustralianGovernment pressuring Telecom to purchase Australian-made products andservices where possible.andP;  Even when the second carrier licence is awarded,Telecom will still be required to pursue a &quot;Buy Australian&quot; policy.andM;Despite the apparently hard line by Telecom, the Australian ElectricalManufacturers' Association (AEEMA) feels that local electronics companies didnot take advantage of the &quot;Buy Australian&quot; policy.andP;  The official AEEMA lineis that both Telecom and the new carrier &quot;will continue to benefit from lowerprices in future as cost reductions from changes to technology and lowercomponent prices will be passed on by industry.&quot;andM;(Sean McNamara/19910506)</TEXT></DOC>